The standard approach in .NET is to **abstract the file system behind an interface** so you can swap in a mock during tests. Two options:

### Option 1: `System.IO.Abstractions` (recommended)

Install the NuGet package — it wraps every `System.IO` static call behind `IFileSystem`:

```csharp
// Production code — inject IFileSystem via DI
public class ConfigLoader(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path) => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);
}

// Tests — use the built-in mock
var fs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/config.json", new MockFileData("{ }") }
});
var loader = new ConfigLoader(fs);
```

```
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### Option 2: Roll your own thin interface

```csharp
public interface IFileSystem
{
    string ReadAllText(string path);
    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);
    bool DirectoryExists(string path);
}
```

Then implement it with the real `System.IO` calls and mock it in tests.

**Go with Option 1** — it covers the entire `System.IO` surface, is well-maintained, and the `MockFileSystem` keeps an in-memory file system so tests stay fast and deterministic.
